05360nam a22007815i 9780674074521DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979588810  a97806740745217 a10.4159/harvard.97806740745212doi  a(DE-B1597)210460  a(OCoLC)842262295  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aSPO0290002bisacsh04a796.5222211 aHansen, Peter H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Summits of Modern Man :bMountaineering after the Enlightenment /cPeter H. Hansen. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b24 halftones, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tCHAPTER ONE Beginnings -- tCHAPTER TWO Discovery of the Glacières -- tCHAPTER THREE Ascent and Enfranchisement -- tCHAPTER FOUR Who Was First? -- tCHAPTER FIVE Temple of Nature -- tCHAPTER SIX Social Climbers -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Age of Conquest -- tCHAPTER EIGHT History Detectives -- tCHAPTER NINE Almost Together -- tCHAPTER TEN Bodies of Ice -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of mountaineering has long served as a metaphor for civilization triumphant. Once upon a time, the Alps were an inaccessible habitat of specters and dragons, until heroic men—pioneers of enlightenment—scaled their summits, classified their strata and flora, and banished the phantoms forever. A fascinating interdisciplinary study of the first ascents of the major Alpine peaks and Mount Everest, The Summits of Modern Man surveys the far-ranging significance of our encounters with the world’s most alluring and forbidding heights. Our obsession with “who got to the top first” may have begun in 1786, the year Jacques Balmat and Michel-Gabriel Paccard climbed Mont Blanc and inaugurated an era in which Romantic notions of the sublime spurred climbers’ aspirations. In the following decades, climbing lost its revolutionary cachet as it became associated instead with bourgeois outdoor leisure. Still, the mythic stories of mountaineers, threaded through with themes of imperialism, masculinity, and ascendant Western science and culture, seized the imagination of artists and historians well into the twentieth century, providing grist for stage shows, poetry, films, and landscape paintings. Today, we live on the threshold of a hot planet, where melting glaciers and rising sea levels create ambivalence about the conquest of nature. Long after Hillary and Tenzing’s ascent of Everest, though, the image of modern man supreme on the mountaintop retains its currency. Peter Hansen’s exploration of these persistent images indicates how difficult it is to imagine our relationship with nature in terms other than domination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMountaineeringxHistory. 0aMountaineeringxPhilosophy. 0aMountaineering. 0aSport. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Mountaineering.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE HISTORY, POLITICAL SCIENCE, SOCIOLOGY  2013z978311031712108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET GESCHICHTE, POLITIKWISS., SOZIOLOGIE  2013z9783110317114oZDB-23-DPS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067407452140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978067407452142